%h1 MyApnea.Org and the Sleep Apnea Patient Centered Outcomes Network
.row
  .col-md-10
    %p The Sleep Apnea Patient Centered Outcomes Network (SAPCON) is the formal network name for MyApnea.Org. It is coordinated by the American Sleep Apnea Association and the Division of Sleep and Circadian Disorders at Brigham and Women’s Hospital, Harvard Medical School, under the guidance of Principal Investigator Susan Redline, M.D., M.P.H. The MyApnea.Org network is part of a historic national research endeavor that will ultimately enlist 100 million people to provide personal health data to guide the course of comparative effectiveness research for multiple, serious, and chronic diseases. Funded by the Patient-Centered Outcomes Research Institute (PCORI), MyApnea.org/SAPCON is one of 18 Patient-Powered Research Networks (PPRN) that will comprise a national “network of networks” dedicated to conducting comparative effectiveness research. It is an unprecedented effort that will redefine how health research is done in this country, and it holds tremendous promise for people who suffer from these conditions.
.row
  .col-md-10
    %h2 Our Funder
    %h3
      = link_to "Patient-Centered Outcomes Research Institute (PCORI)", 'http://www.pcori.org/funding-opportunities/pcornet-national-patient-centered-clinical-research-network/'
    %p The Patient-Centered Outcomes Research Institute (PCORI) is an independent, non-profit organization authorized by Congress in 2010 to fund research aimed at improving the health of entire populations.
    %p In December 2013, the Patient-Centered Outcomes Research Institute approved $93.5 million to support 29 clinical research data networks that together will form an ambitious new resource known as PCORnet, or the National Patient-Centered Outcomes Clinical Research Network. PCORnet will be a large, highly representative, national network for conducting clinical outcomes research. PCORnet will integrate data from 11 Clinical Data Research Networks—networks that originate in healthcare systems such as hospitals, health plans, and practice-based networks and securely collect real-time health information during the routine course of patient care—and 18 Patient-Powered Research Networks—networks operated and governed by groups of patients and their partners who are focused on a particular condition and interested in sharing health information and participating in research.
